Deploying AWS Lambda using serverless deploy (ZIP package) vs Amazon ECR images (container deployment) are two different packaging models. Both run on Lambda, but they differ in build process, limits, startup behavior, and operational style.

Quick Summary
Topic			Serverless Deploy (ZIP)			ECR Images (Container)
Package Type		ZIP artifact				Docker image
Max Size			50 MB zipped / 250 MB unzipped		Up to 10 GB
Deploy Command		serverless deploy			Build image + push + update Lambda
Best For			APIs, small/medium functions		Large apps, native deps, custom runtimes
Runtime			AWS managed runtime			AWS base image or custom image
Cold Start		Usually smaller/faster if slim		Can be slower if image is large
DevOps Complexity	Lower					Higher
Local Reproducibility	Moderate				Strong (same container locally/cloud)
Native Binaries		Sometimes 				tricky	Easier
Security Patching	Mostly runtime managed by AWS		You manage image updates

1. serverless deploy (ZIP package)
    Usually done with Serverless Framework.
	
	serverless deploy					Limitations
	✅ Simpler CI/CD					⚠️ Package size limits
	✅ Faster deployments for smaller codebases		⚠️ Native libraries can be painful (sharp)
	✅ Less Docker overhead					⚠️ Harder to fully mirror prod locally 
	✅ Easier for most Node.js apps

2. ECR Image Deployment
    You package the Lambda as a Docker image and push to Amazon ECR.

    Dockerfile
	FROM public.ecr.aws/lambda/nodejs:20
	COPY . .
	CMD ["handler.handler"]

   Then:
	docker build -t my-lambda .
	docker tag my-lambda:latest <ecr-repo-uri>:latest
	docker push <ecr-repo-uri>:latest

	Lambda pulls the image.

    Advantages							Limitations
	✅ Up to 10 GB image size				⚠️ More DevOps steps	
	✅ Full control of environment				⚠️ Must maintain base image updates
	✅ Easier native dependencies				⚠️ Large images can slow cold starts
	✅ Strong reproducibility
